subSubSection.paragraph: (female terminalia). Type locality: United States , New Mexico , Las Vegas. Distr.– United States ( New Mexico ), Mexico (Guadalajara).

Remarks.
Swammerdamella marginata
is a very small scatopsid, ranging from 1.30 to 1.40 mm . The type locality of
S. marginata
is Las Vegas, New Mexico . Cook (1965a) also referred to specimens of this species from additional sites in southern California (San Bernardino, Davis, Riverside, Los Angeles etc.) and Nevada (Reno). The record for Guadalajara, Mexico , may be questionable, but we did not examine the original specimens identified by Cook (1965a) .

This was the most abundant species in our samples, with up to 66.1% of the total number of scatopsid specimens of the project: a total of 367 males and 1,315 females were identified in the sorted samples. The species appeared at 39 of the 47 BioSCAN collecting sites, in a total of 182 collecting events. The most abundant collecting sites for
S. marginata
were 5, 18, 19, 28, and 30. As happened with
Quateiella quatei
, there is a clear peak of abundance of
S. marginata
in early-mid-spring, with a second peak in mid-autumn.

There is no information available on the biology of
S. marginata
. In North America, there are records of adults of
S. pygmaea (Loew)
associated to flowers of
Staphylea floralis
( Staphyleaceae ) ( Cook 1956b ).
Staphylea
has species native to eastern North America and to California (USDA 2019), but no connection so far of this plant genus with
S. marginata
has been formally proposed. In South America, there is a record of emergence of a species of a
Swammerdamella
over piles of rotting grass (D.S.A., personal observation). The BOLDSystems has one single specimen of
Swammerdamella
sequenced for Australia , most certainly not
S. marginata
.
